    <text>
        <body>
            <head>24. Memorandum From Acting Secretary of State <persName
                    corresp="rec9EBLnqQPcxRtYr">Christopher</persName> to President <persName
                    corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d24fn1">Source: Carter Library,
                    National Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Brzezinski Office File, Country
                    Chron File, Box 7, Chad. Confidential. Sent to <persName
                        corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName> under an August 30 covering
                    memorandum from <persName corresp="rectQC2yY4UhXLeKu">Brzezinski</persName>, who
                    recommended the President sign the <rs corresp="recKz0w91lnkAu1cS" type="topic"
                        >Determination</rs>.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1977-08-20"
                        >August 20, 1977</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Eligibility of <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> to
                    Purchase <rs type="topic" corresp="recOz4p561G66Gv2s">Defense Articles</rs> and
                    Defense Services under the <rs corresp="recf7oWPDGyUlNNf7">Arms Export Control
                        Act</rs>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Problem</p>
            <p>You are asked to find that the sale of <rs type="topic" corresp="recOz4p561G66Gv2s"
                    >defense articles</rs> and defense services under the <rs
                    corresp="recf7oWPDGyUlNNf7">Arms Export Control Act</rs> (the Act) to <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> will strengthen the <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recT2lnbrCcFQqokm">security</rs> of the <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName> and promote world peace.
                Your finding will assist the <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">United
                    States Government</rs> in responding positively to a Chadian request for
                approval to purchase <rs type="topic" corresp="recJ9z9SORjaCLZG1">military
                    equipment</rs> and training on a government-to-government basis under <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">Foreign Military Sales</rs> (<gloss
                    target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss>) procedures. This would be the first new country made <gloss
                    target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> eligible by your <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv"
                    >Administration</rs>.</p>
            <pb facs="0067" n="46" xml:id="pg_46"/>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Background</p>
            <p>
                <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>’s request for <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recOz4p561G66Gv2s">defense articles</rs> and services from
                the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName> results from
                its unsuccessful efforts to quell an insurgency in northern <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> that has been receiving increased
                military support from <placeName corresp="recHYRQHh3kc1bSkH">Libya</placeName>. On
                July 15, Vice President <persName corresp="rechYUJdMMxy4Djaf">Mondale</persName>
                told the Chadian Vice President that we would assist in restoring <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>’s <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recAPhAIrM8XS4R2T">territorial integrity</rs>.<note n="2" place="foot"
                    xml:id="d24fn2">See <ref target="#d18fn2">footnote 2, Document 18</ref>.</note>
                The Government of <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> has
                requested assistance from other governments as well as the <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName> to stabilize the
                situation.</p>
            <p>I believe it is in our <rs type="topic" corresp="recT2lnbrCcFQqokm">security</rs>
                interest to work with <placeName corresp="recJuFaVGGmK95QOO">France</placeName> and
                other interested governments to ensure that the internal security of <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> does not further deteriorate, and
                to ensure that <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> can assert
                control over its territory to the maximum extent possible.</p>
            <p>If you approve this <rs corresp="recKz0w91lnkAu1cS" type="topic">Determination</rs>,
                we would plan, subject to your agreement, to establish the military supply
                relationship with <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> on the
                understanding that it would be designed essentially to meet the current problem and
                would not be enduring. The principal purpose of your <rs corresp="recKz0w91lnkAu1cS"
                    type="topic">Determination</rs> would be to gain the authority to permit third
                country transfers. However, we would also wish to be in a position to authorize
                government-to-government sales of equipment which we have indicated to <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> we are prepared to provide. While
                our strong preference would be for third countries to finance such purchases, we
                plan to include a small amount of <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> credit for <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> in our
                preparations for the <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 1979 budget submissions in
                the event other countries prove unwilling to finance <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>’s military needs.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Legal Considerations</p>
            <p>
                <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> is not at present eligible
                to purchase <rs type="topic" corresp="recOz4p561G66Gv2s">defense articles</rs> and
                services on a government-to-government basis. Section 3(a)(1) of the Act provides as
                one of the conditions of eligibility for any foreign country to purchase <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recOz4p561G66Gv2s">defense articles</rs> or defense
                services from the <rs type="event" corresp="rec2z1tbfKZPT8edv">United States
                    Government</rs> that the President find that such sales will “strengthen the <rs
                    type="topic" corresp="recT2lnbrCcFQqokm">security</rs> of the <placeName
                    corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName> and promote world peace.”
                Authority to make this finding is reserved to the President by Section 1(a) of
                Executive Order 11958 of January 18, 1977. Section 3(a) of the Act also provides
                that consent may not be given to the proposed transfer from a third party of <gloss
                    target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss>-origin <rs type="topic" corresp="recOz4p561G66Gv2s">defense articles</rs>
                or services unless the <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United
                    States</placeName> would itself transfer the articles and services in question
                to the proposed recipient.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Other considerations</p>
            <p>Because the equipment which we would consider for transfer to <placeName
                    corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName> would be limited in quantity,
                variety and sophistication, your <pb facs="0068" n="47" xml:id="pg_47"/>
                <rs corresp="recKz0w91lnkAu1cS" type="topic">determination</rs> of eligibility would
                not be inconsistent with your general <rs type="topic" corresp="rec9ptkWICFUk7Mvu"
                    >arms transfer</rs> policy.</p>
            <p>
                <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>’s <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recVSPQM8CicmOme2">human rights</rs> record has improved considerably
                under the military regime that came to power following the April 1975 coup d’etat.
                Though arbitrary arrests of suspect guerrillas have occurred, most detainees are
                quickly either brought to trial or released.</p>
            <p>Preliminary soundings indicate that we must expect some <orgName
                    corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM">Congressional</orgName> opposition to expanding the
                list of countries eligible for <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">
                    <rs type="topic" corresp="recM6MmQNEwIZpchW">FMS</rs>
                </gloss> sales in light of your avowed <rs corresp="recKz0w91lnkAu1cS" type="topic"
                    >determination</rs> to reduce <rs type="topic" corresp="recYitJjr1dXM44FB">arms
                    sales</rs> worldwide. We doubt, however, given the limited nature of any likely
                sales to <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>, that there will be
                a major opposition to declaring <placeName corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn"
                    >Chad</placeName> eligible to purchase <rs type="topic"
                    corresp="recOz4p561G66Gv2s">defense articles</rs> and services from the
                    <placeName corresp="recxXt2KOngYAhHuL">United States</placeName>. Although not
                required by law, we believe notification to <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM"
                    >Congress</orgName> and publication of the <rs corresp="recKz0w91lnkAu1cS"
                    type="topic">Determination</rs> in the <hi rendition="simple_italic">Federal
                    Register</hi> will be helpful in its implementation.</p>
            <p rendition="#sectiontitleital">Recommendation</p>
            <p>I recommend that you approve and sign the attached <rs corresp="recKz0w91lnkAu1cS"
                    type="topic">Determination</rs>, thereby also approving the attached
                justification therefor. The <orgName corresp="recjQ97iMHKp6vwlA">Department of
                    Defense</orgName> concurs. In accordance with established procedures, your <rs
                    corresp="recKz0w91lnkAu1cS" type="topic">Determination</rs> and the attached
                justification therefor will be furnished to the <orgName corresp="recmLoDjMiF4yt3cM"
                    >Congress</orgName>. The <rs corresp="recKz0w91lnkAu1cS" type="topic"
                    >Determination</rs> alone will be published in the <hi rendition="simple_italic"
                    >Federal Register</hi>.<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d24fn3">Not attached.
                        <rs corresp="recKz0w91lnkAu1cS" type="topic">Presidential Determination</rs>
                    No. 77–20, signed by <persName corresp="reccm3OnsdQpGeNR8">Carter</persName> on
                    September 1, is in the Carter Library, National Security Affairs, Brzezinski
                    Material, Brzezinski Office File, Country Chron File, Box 7, <placeName
                        corresp="recYyQtgN8smHlecn">Chad</placeName>.</note>
            </p>
        </body>
